var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"location":"benchmarks/#Benchmarks","page":"Benchmarks","title":"Benchmarks","text":"This page describes the standard front-tracking benchmarks implemented in FrontTrackingMethods.jl v0.2.  Each benchmark is available through the reusable helpers in src/benchmark_geometries.jl and src/benchmark_fields.jl, which are called by the test suite and by the example scripts in examples/.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#2-D-Rigid-Motions","page":"Benchmarks","title":"2-D Rigid Motions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#Circle-rotation-(rigid-body)","page":"Benchmarks","title":"Circle rotation (rigid body)","text":"Geometry: circle centered at (0.5, 0.75), radius 0.15.   Field: rigid_rotation_2d(; center=(0.5,0.5), omega=2π) — one full revolution per unit time.   Final time: T = 1.0.   What it stresses: time-integration accuracy, area preservation of the polygon.   Primary metrics: centroid return error, relative area drift, Hausdorff distance to initial.   Exact reversibility: yes — all errors should be due to time-integration truncation only.","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#Circle-translation","page":"Benchmarks","title":"Circle translation","text":"Field: rigid_translation_velocity(u).   What it stresses: pure transport accuracy (all errors should be machine precision).   Primary metrics: centroid error, area error.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#2-D-Zalesak-disk-rotation","page":"Benchmarks","title":"2-D Zalesak disk rotation","text":"Reference: Zalesak (1979), \"Fully Multidimensional Flux-Corrected Transport\".\n\nGeometry: slotted disk centered at (0.5, 0.75), radius 0.15, slot width 0.05, slot depth 0.25. Built by make_zalesak_disk_curve.   Field: rigid-body rotation about (0.5, 0.5), ω = 2π.   Final time: T = 1.0.   What it stresses: preservation of sharp slot corners, area conservation under redistribution.   Primary metrics: area drift, centroid drift, Hausdorff distance to initial front.   Expected behavior: the slot opening should remain clearly recognizable after one revolution.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#2-D-Rider–Kothe-Reversed-Single-Vortex","page":"Benchmarks","title":"2-D Rider–Kothe Reversed Single Vortex","text":"Reference: Rider & Kothe (1998), \"Reconstructing Volume Tracking\".\n\nGeometry: circle centered at (0.5, 0.75), radius 0.15.   Field: rider_kothe_single_vortex(; T=2.0) — stream-function-based solenoidal field, reversed at T/2.   Final time: T = 2.0.   What it stresses: interface stretching and filament formation; reversibility under time reversal; redistribution quality.   Primary metrics: shape recovery (Hausdorff / L² distance to initial), area drift.   Exact reversibility: yes in the exact case; numerical errors are non-zero.   Note: redistribution/remeshing should materially improve final-time shape recovery.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#2-D-Strong-Deformation-(16-Vortex)","page":"Benchmarks","title":"2-D Strong Deformation (16-Vortex)","text":"Geometry: circle centered at (0.5, 0.75), radius 0.15.   Field: deformation16_2d(; T=2.0) — periodic stream-function field with 16 vortices, reversed at T/2.   What it stresses: severe shear-stretch, robustness of redistribution under strong deformation.   Primary metrics: minimum edge length (collapse indicator), shape recovery error.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#2-D-Serpentine-Deformation","page":"Benchmarks","title":"2-D Serpentine Deformation","text":"Reference: LeVeque (1996), \"High-resolution conservative algorithms for advection in incompressible flow\".\n\nGeometry: circle centered at (0.5, 0.75), radius 0.15.   Field: serpentine_2d(; Tmax=3.0) — divergence-free serpentine flow, reversed at Tmax/2.   Final time: Tmax = 3.0.   What it stresses: long-filament formation, severe shear, marker redistribution under extreme stretch.   Primary metrics: L² and Hausdorff shape recovery, relative area drift, minimum edge length.   Note: this is the most demanding 2-D reversible test.  Redistribution is mandatory to prevent catastrophic marker collapse.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#3-D-Rigid-Motions","page":"Benchmarks","title":"3-D Rigid Motions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#Sphere-translation","page":"Benchmarks","title":"Sphere translation","text":"Geometry: sphere centered at (0.35, 0.35, 0.35), radius 0.15.   Field: rigid_translation_velocity(u).   Primary metrics: centroid error (should be near machine precision), volume drift.","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#Sphere-rotation","page":"Benchmarks","title":"Sphere rotation","text":"Geometry: sphere centered at (0.5, 0.75, 0.5), radius 0.15.   Field: rigid_rotation_3d(; center=(0.5,0.5,0.5), axis=:z, omega=2π).   Final time: T = 1.0.   Primary metrics: centroid return error, volume drift, Hausdorff to initial.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#3-D-Zalesak-Sphere-Rotation","page":"Benchmarks","title":"3-D Zalesak Sphere Rotation","text":"Geometry: slotted sphere built by make_zalesak_sphere_surface.   Field: rigid-body rotation.   What it stresses: fixed-topology surface tracking under rigid motion, slot-corner preservation on a triangulated mesh.   Primary metrics (v0.2): surface-area drift, centroid drift, symmetric Hausdorff to initial, slot-region proxy distance.   Important limitation: the current slotted-sphere constructor is approximate and not guaranteed closed at coarse resolution, so enclosed-volume drift is not the primary metric here.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"benchmarks/#3-D-Enright-Deformation","page":"Benchmarks","title":"3-D Enright Deformation","text":"Reference: Enright et al. (2002), \"A Hybrid Particle Level Set Method for Improved Interface Tracking\".\n\nGeometry: sphere centered at (0.35, 0.35, 0.35), radius 0.15, in a unit cube.   Field: enright_3d(; T=3.0) — divergence-free prescribed velocity, reversed at T/2.   Final time: T = 3.0.   What it stresses: severe surface deformation into thin sheets; volume preservation; surface mesh quality degradation.   Primary metrics:\n\nfinal volume drift\nsurface area drift\napproximate symmetric Hausdorff distance to initial sphere\nquality over time (minimum triangle angle, degenerate-triangle fraction)\n\nWhich metric to check first: for Enright, check symmetric Hausdorff (shape recovery) first, then volume drift, then quality-over-time.   Note: surface remeshing is often helpful but remains experimental; benchmark studies should compare remeshing-enabled and no-remeshing runs.","category":"section"},{"location":"api/#API-summary","page":"API Reference","title":"API summary","text":"The package exposes a compact, high-level API. This page lists the primary types and functions; consult docstrings in src/ for details.\n\nCore types and constructors\n\nFrontField(values, mesh, location) — attach per-vertex/edge/face fields.\nFrontState(mesh; t=0.0) — front geometry with attached fields and time.\nFrontEquation(; front, terms, integrator, redistributor, callback...) — top-level equation object.\n\nMotion terms\n\nAdvectionTerm(u) — prescribed vector velocity (constant or function).\nNormalMotionTerm(Vn) — scalar normal speed (positive means inward for CCW curves).\nCurvatureMotionTerm(β) — curvature-driven normal motion.\n\nIntegrators\n\nForwardEuler, RK2, RK3 — explicit time-stepping integrators.\n\nRedistributors / Remeshing\n\nNoRedistribution — do nothing.\nCurveEqualArcRedistributor — equal-arc redistribution on curves.\nAdaptiveCurveRemesher — fixed-topology adaptive remesher with corner protection.\nSurfaceTangentialRedistributor — tangential smoothing on surfaces.\nExperimentalSurfaceRemesher — experimental fixed-topology surface quality remesher.\n\nCore functions\n\nintegrate!(eq, T; dt, callback...) — advance solution to time T.\ncurrent_state(eq) / current_time(eq) — query running equation.\nrefresh_geometry!(state) — recompute geometry (normals, curvature, areas).\nredistribute!(state, redistributor) / remesh!(...) — redistribute or remesh.\ntransfer_vertex_field!(...) — transfer fields between meshes (:piecewise_linear, :nearest_vertex, :barycentric).\nadd_field!(state, name, values; location=:vertex) — attach a field.\n\nDiagnostics & metrics\n\nfront_enclosed_measure, front_measure, front_centroid, edge_length_spread\nsurface_edge_length_stats, surface_triangle_area_stats, surface_triangle_angle_stats\nsurface_aspect_ratio_stats, surface_degenerate_fraction, surface_quality_summary\nsymmetric_hausdorff_curve, l2_distance_curve, relative_area_error\n\nCallbacks\n\nEveryNSteps(n, callback) — call callback(state, t, step) every n steps.\nTimeIntervalCallback(dt, callback) — call callback at wall-clock time intervals.\n\nFor function signatures and examples, inspect the docstrings in the corresponding src/*.jl files (the module exports a compact set of names).","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Quick-start-/-Usage","page":"Usage","title":"Quick start / Usage","text":"This quick start demonstrates the typical workflow: construct a front, define motion terms, assemble a FrontEquation, and call integrate!.\n\nusing FrontIntrinsicOps, FrontTrackingMethods, StaticArrays\n\n# Build a circle mesh\nN = 64; R = 1.0\npts   = [SVector(R*cos(2π*(i-1)/N), R*sin(2π*(i-1)/N)) for i in 1:N]\nedges = [SVector(i, mod1(i+1,N)) for i in 1:N]\nmesh  = CurveMesh(pts, edges)\n\n# Define motion: constant advection\nu_adv = SVector(0.2, -0.1)\nterms = (AdvectionTerm(u_adv),)\n\n# Build equation and integrate for T=1.0\neq = FrontEquation(; terms=terms, front=mesh, t=0.0, integrator=RK2())\nintegrate!(eq, 1.0)\n\n# Inspect final state\nstate = current_state(eq)\nprintln(\"centroid: \", front_centroid(state))\n\nRedistribution and remeshing are purely numerical: call redistribute! or pass a redistributor to FrontEquation or use callbacks such as EveryNSteps.","category":"section"},{"location":"usage/#Surface-field-transfer","page":"Usage","title":"Surface field transfer","text":"When redistribution/remeshing moves vertices, transfer vertex fields with transfer_vertex_field!:\n\ntransfer_vertex_field!(dst, oldmesh, srcvals, newmesh; method=:barycentric)\n\n:nearest_vertex is the simplest fallback.\n:barycentric is generally preferred on surfaces for smooth fields and\n\npreserves constants exactly.","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Redistribution-and-Remeshing","page":"Remeshing","title":"Redistribution and Remeshing","text":"This page explains the difference between physical motion and numerical redistribution / remeshing, and documents the redistribution and remeshing strategies available in FrontTrackingMethods.jl v0.2.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Physical-motion-vs.-numerical-redistribution","page":"Remeshing","title":"Physical motion vs. numerical redistribution","text":"Physical motion is governed by the PDE:\n\ndx/dt = u(x, t)\n\nwhere u is the prescribed velocity field.  The integrators (RK2, RK3, ForwardEuler) advance the marker positions according to this equation.\n\nRedistribution / remeshing is a purely numerical operation that repositions or restructures the front mesh without affecting the physical interface.  Its purpose is to maintain good mesh quality so that the physical motion can be integrated accurately.\n\nKey principle: redistribution must not be confused with topology change or interface diffusion.  A good redistributor preserves the interface geometry while improving marker distribution.\n\nRedistribution is triggered by calling redistribute!(state, redistributor) or by supplying a redistributor to FrontEquation.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Curve-redistributors","page":"Remeshing","title":"Curve redistributors","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#CurveEqualArcRedistributor","page":"Remeshing","title":"CurveEqualArcRedistributor","text":"Redistributes markers uniformly along the arc length of the current curve. Vertex count is preserved.\n\nr = CurveEqualArcRedistributor(; every=1)\nredistribute!(state, r)\n\nProperties:\n\npreserves closure\npreserves vertex count\narea change is typically < 1%\ndoes not protect corners\n\nRecommended for: smooth interfaces where uniform spacing is sufficient.","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#AdaptiveCurveRemesher-(v0.2)","page":"Remeshing","title":"AdaptiveCurveRemesher (v0.2)","text":"A fixed-topology adaptive remesher for curves.\n\nr = AdaptiveCurveRemesher(;\n    iterations      = 5,      # number of smoothing passes\n    protect_corners = true,   # protect sharp-corner vertices from smoothing\n    corner_angle    = π/4,    # turning angle threshold for corner detection\n)\nredistribute!(state, r)\n\nProperties:\n\nfixed topology (no vertex insertion / deletion by default)\noptional corner protection for Zalesak-like geometries\npreserves closure\narea change is typically < 2% with default settings\n\nRecommended for: Zalesak disk, serpentine flow, any interface with sharp geometric features that should be preserved.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Surface-redistributors","page":"Remeshing","title":"Surface redistributors","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#SurfaceTangentialRedistributor","page":"Remeshing","title":"SurfaceTangentialRedistributor","text":"Laplacian tangential smoothing for surface meshes.  Vertices are moved in the tangent plane of the local surface; the normal component is projected back onto the surface.\n\nr = SurfaceTangentialRedistributor(; iterations=3, strength=0.5)\nredistribute!(state, r)\n\nStatus: usable for mild/moderate 3-D deformation in v0.2.   Properties:\n\nno topology change\nvolume change is typically < 5%\nstrength in [0, 1]; lower values are more conservative\n\nRecommended for: sphere translation/rotation and modest deformation tests.","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#ExperimentalSurfaceRemesher-*(experimental)*","page":"Remeshing","title":"ExperimentalSurfaceRemesher (experimental)","text":"A conservative fixed-topology surface remesher for robustness studies. It combines:\n\ntangential centroid relaxation,\nedge-length regularization toward [lmin, lmax],\nlocal area-based move rejection to avoid degeneracy,\noptional mild global volume correction.\n\nr = ExperimentalSurfaceRemesher(;\n    iterations=3,\n    strength=0.25,\n    lmin=nothing,\n    lmax=nothing,\n    min_area=1e-14,\n    volume_correction=true,\n    volume_relaxation=0.15,\n)\nredistribute!(state, r)\n\nStatus: experimental in v0.2.  API may change.   Properties:\n\nno topology change\ndeterministic conservative updates\navoids accepting local moves that create near-degenerate triangles\nuseful for benchmark robustness, not yet a full production remeshing framework\n\nThreshold/tuning notes:\n\nlmin, lmax: if omitted, inferred from current mean edge length.\nmin_area: larger values are safer but may under-correct poor meshes.\nmax_tangential_step: limits per-pass vertex displacement.\nvolume_correction=true is only applied on closed surfaces.\n\nRecommended for: Enright 3-D deformation benchmark on longer runs.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Fixed-topology-scope","page":"Remeshing","title":"Fixed-topology scope","text":"v0.2 remeshing is fixed topology: no edge insertion, edge collapse, edge flip, or hole creation. Vertex/face connectivity is preserved for surface redistributors and remeshers.\n\nTopology-changing remeshing (e.g., vertex insertion for long edges) is planned for v0.3 and is not part of this release.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Controlling-redistribution-frequency","page":"Remeshing","title":"Controlling redistribution frequency","text":"Redistribution can be controlled in two ways:","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Per-step-via-redistribute_every-(CurveEqualArcRedistributor)","page":"Remeshing","title":"Per-step via redistribute_every (CurveEqualArcRedistributor)","text":"r = CurveEqualArcRedistributor(; every=5)  # redistribute every 5 steps","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#Via-EveryNSteps-callback","page":"Remeshing","title":"Via EveryNSteps callback","text":"cb = EveryNSteps(5, (state, t, step) -> redistribute!(state, my_remesher))\nintegrate!(eq, T; dt=dt, callback=cb)\n\nThis pattern is useful when you want to redistribute less frequently than every step, or when redistribution should depend on mesh quality.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"remeshing/#remesh!-alias","page":"Remeshing","title":"remesh! alias","text":"remesh! is an alias for redistribute!:\n\nremesh!(state, r)   # same as redistribute!(state, r)","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Diagnostics","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Diagnostics","text":"This page defines the front-tracking diagnostic metrics available in FrontTrackingMethods.jl v0.2 and explains why each is necessary.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Why-volume-preservation-alone-is-not-enough","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Why volume preservation alone is not enough","text":"A common mistake in interface-tracking is to report only volume / area preservation.  Volume preservation is necessary but not sufficient:\n\nA highly distorted front that has lost its physical shape can still have the correct volume if marker points have been redistributed aggressively.\nVolume-only metrics do not penalize shape diffusion, loss of sharp corners, filament tearing, or numerical dissipation of the front geometry.\n\nFor a complete assessment of an interface-tracking method, you need:\n\nVolume / area conservation — global, easy to compute, necessary.\nCentroid position error — detects systematic drift or spurious translation.\nFront-to-front geometric error — detects shape diffusion and filament loss.\nMesh quality metrics — detect marker collapse / degenerate elements.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Shape-integral-diagnostics","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Shape-integral diagnostics","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#relative_area_error(mesh,-mesh_ref)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"relative_area_error(mesh, mesh_ref)","text":"Relative signed area difference:\n\n(area(mesh) - area(mesh_ref)) / area(mesh_ref)\n\nFor curves.  Positive means the mesh has grown; negative means it has shrunk.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#relative_volume_error(mesh,-mesh_ref)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"relative_volume_error(mesh, mesh_ref)","text":"Same as above for surfaces (enclosed volume).","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#centroid_error(mesh,-mesh_ref)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"centroid_error(mesh, mesh_ref)","text":"Euclidean distance between the vertex centroids of the two meshes.\n\n‖centroid(mesh) - centroid(mesh_ref)‖₂","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#perimeter_error(mesh,-mesh_ref)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"perimeter_error(mesh, mesh_ref)","text":"Relative difference in total arc length (curve perimeter).","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_area_error(mesh,-mesh_ref)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_area_error(mesh, mesh_ref)","text":"Relative difference in total surface area.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Front-to-front-geometric-error","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Front-to-front geometric error","text":"These metrics measure how well two front meshes agree geometrically, without assuming vertex-to-vertex correspondence.  They are essential for reversible benchmark tests where the initial and final fronts should coincide.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#nearest_distance_curve_to_curve(meshA,-meshB)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"nearest_distance_curve_to_curve(meshA, meshB)","text":"For each vertex of meshA, find the minimum distance to any segment of meshB.  Returns the maximum such distance (one-sided Hausdorff).","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#symmetric_hausdorff_curve(meshA,-meshB)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"symmetric_hausdorff_curve(meshA, meshB)","text":"max(nearest_distance_curve_to_curve(A,B),\n    nearest_distance_curve_to_curve(B,A))\n\nThe approximate symmetric Hausdorff distance between two curves.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#l2_distance_curve(meshA,-meshB;-nsamples1000)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"l2_distance_curve(meshA, meshB; nsamples=1000)","text":"An approximate L² distance between two curves computed by sampling nsamples uniformly-spaced points on meshA and summing squared nearest distances to meshB.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#3-D-equivalents","page":"Diagnostics","title":"3-D equivalents","text":"nearest_distance_surface_to_surface, symmetric_hausdorff_surface, and l2_distance_surface provide the same functionality for surface meshes.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Mesh-quality-metrics","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Mesh quality metrics","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#edge_length_spread(state)-/-edge_length_stats(mesh)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"edge_length_spread(state) / edge_length_stats(mesh)","text":"The ratio max_edge_length / min_edge_length.  A spread close to 1 means uniform spacing; a large spread indicates clustering that will degrade numerical accuracy or cause stability issues.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#min_edge_length(state)-/-max_edge_length(state)-/-mean_edge_length(state)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"min_edge_length(state) / max_edge_length(state) / mean_edge_length(state)","text":"Basic edge-length statistics.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#triangle_quality_stats(mesh::SurfaceMesh)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"triangle_quality_stats(mesh::SurfaceMesh)","text":"Returns minimum triangle angle and mean aspect ratio.  Low minimum angle (< 5°) or high aspect ratio (> 20) indicate degenerate elements that will cause integration errors.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_edge_length_stats(mesh)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_edge_length_stats(mesh)","text":"Returns (min, max, mean, std, ratio) for surface edge lengths, with ratio = max/min.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_triangle_area_stats(mesh)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_triangle_area_stats(mesh)","text":"Returns (min, max, mean) for triangle areas.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_triangle_angle_stats(mesh)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_triangle_angle_stats(mesh)","text":"Returns (min_angle, max_angle, mean_min_angle) in radians.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_aspect_ratio_stats(mesh)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_aspect_ratio_stats(mesh)","text":"Returns (min, max, mean) using\n\naspect = (lmax * perimeter) / (4 * sqrt(3) * area)\n\nfor each triangle (1 for equilateral).","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_degenerate_fraction(mesh;-atol...)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_degenerate_fraction(mesh; atol=...)","text":"Fraction of triangles with area <= atol.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_quality_summary(mesh)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_quality_summary(mesh)","text":"Compact named-tuple aggregation of edge, area, angle, aspect, and degenerate fraction metrics.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#surface_normal_consistency(mesh,-geom)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"surface_normal_consistency(mesh, geom)","text":"Optional orientation-consistency diagnostic based on alignment between face normals and averaged vertex normals.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#check_front_validity(state;-warntrue)","page":"Diagnostics","title":"check_front_validity(state; warn=true)","text":"Returns true if the front passes basic sanity checks:\n\nno NaN / Inf vertices\ncorrect number of edges / faces\nnon-zero area / volume\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Why-front-to-front-geometric-error-matters","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Why front-to-front geometric error matters","text":"Consider the Rider–Kothe reversed vortex benchmark.  A method may preserve area nearly perfectly while completely destroying the filament shape:\n\nNo redistribution: the interface stretches into a filament and markers cluster near the tips.  Volume is preserved because markers cannot cross. But the filament becomes unresolved and the Hausdorff distance to the initial front is large.\nWith redistribution: markers are spread uniformly along the filament. The shape is better resolved and the Hausdorff distance is materially smaller.\n\nThis is why symmetric_hausdorff_curve is the primary shape metric in the reversible benchmark tests, not just area drift.","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/#Examples","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Short descriptions of example scripts included in the repository (examples/).\n\ncurve_shortening_circle.jl — curve-shortening (mean-curvature) flow on a circle.\ndeformation16_2d.jl — 2-D 16-vortex deformation benchmark setup.\nenright_deformation_3d.jl — Enright 3-D deformation smoke test on a coarse sphere.\nexpand_circle_normal_speed.jl — outward normal motion example.\noscillating_drop_2d.jl — periodic 2-D drop oscillation with animation and diagnostic plot.\nredistribute_curve_demo.jl — demonstrates curve redistribution strategies.\nrider_kothe_single_vortex.jl — Rider–Kothe reversible vortex benchmark.\nrotate_circle.jl — circle rigid rotation demo.\nrotate_sphere.jl — rigid rotation demo for a sphere.\nserpentine_2d.jl — serpentine deformation benchmark setup.\ntranslate_circle.jl — translation demo for a circle.\ntranslate_sphere.jl — translation demo for a sphere.\nzalesak_disk_rotation.jl — Zalesak disk rotation demo.\nzalesak_sphere_rotation.jl — coarse 3-D slotted-sphere rigid-rotation benchmark.\n\nTo run an example interactively:\n\njulia --project=. examples/rotate_circle.jl\n\nExamples that evolve fronts now use CairoMakie and write outputs under:\n\nexamples/output/<example_name>/initial.png\nexamples/output/<example_name>/final.png\nexamples/output/<example_name>/animation.mp4\n\nExamples are intentionally small; for longer convergence or benchmarking scripts see the test/ harness and the benchmark_*.jl helpers in src/.","category":"section"},{"location":"testing/#Running-tests","page":"Testing","title":"Running tests","text":"Run the package test-suite from the project root:\n\ncd /path/to/FrontTrackingMethods.jl\njulia --project=. -e 'using Pkg; Pkg.test()'\n\nNotes and tips\n\nThe test harness uses local FrontIntrinsicOps.jl (see Project.toml / Manifest.toml).\nIf you see warnings about replaced modules while developing tests, ensure test/test_utils.jl is only included once (the test dispatcher test/runtests.jl should include test_utils.jl and call using .TestUtils).\nLong convergence/benchmark runs are available in test/ and may take several minutes depending on resolutions and mesh refinements.","category":"section"},{"location":"installation/#Installation","page":"Installation","title":"Installation","text":"Install with the current Julia project activated. If you are developing locally, add the package by path so local changes are used:\n\nusing Pkg\nPkg.develop(path=\".\")   # from the package root\nPkg.resolve()\n\nTo run the test-suite:\n\ncd /path/to/FrontTrackingMethods.jl\njulia --project=. -e 'using Pkg; Pkg.test()'\n\nNotes:\n\nThis package depends on FrontIntrinsicOps.jl. When running locally, ensure FrontIntrinsicOps.jl is available (the test setup uses a local path dependency in the Project/Manifest).\nThe project uses StaticArrays and standard library modules.","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Plotting-and-animations","page":"Plotting and animations","title":"Plotting and animations","text":"FrontTrackingMethods.jl enables plotting through a Makie weak extension. That means plotting APIs become available when a Makie backend is loaded, for example CairoMakie.\n\nusing CairoMakie\nusing FrontIntrinsicOps\nusing FrontTrackingMethods","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Static-plots","page":"Plotting and animations","title":"Static plots","text":"using StaticArrays\n\nmesh = make_circle_benchmark_curve(center=SVector(0.0, 0.0), R=1.0, N=128)\nstate = FrontState(mesh)\n\nset_makie_theme!()\nfig, ax, p = plot_state(state; show_vertices=true, title=\"initial front\")\nsave(\"state.png\", fig)\n\nYou can also plot equation state directly:\n\neq = FrontEquation(; terms=(AdvectionTerm(SVector(1.0, 0.0)),), front=mesh)\nfig, ax, p = plot_equation(eq)\nsave(\"equation.png\", fig)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Snapshots-and-recording","page":"Plotting and animations","title":"Snapshots and recording","text":"High-level helpers are provided by the extension:\n\nsnapshot(obj, filename) for CurveMesh, SurfaceMesh, FrontState, or FrontEquation\nrecord_evolution!(eq, filename, times) to integrate and record a movie\n\ntimes = range(0.0, stop=1.0, length=120)\nsnapshot(eq, \"initial.png\")\nrecord_evolution!(eq, \"front.mp4\", times)\nsnapshot(eq, \"final.png\")","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Notes","page":"Plotting and animations","title":"Notes","text":"Plotting remains optional: core simulation APIs work without Makie.\nCairoMakie is only needed in examples/docs/tests; the package weak-dep is Makie.\nFor low-level mesh plotting (CurveMesh, SurfaceMesh, normals, wireframes), see FrontIntrinsicOps plotting helpers.","category":"section"},{"location":"#FrontTrackingMethods.jl","page":"Home","title":"FrontTrackingMethods.jl","text":"FrontTrackingMethods.jl provides Lagrangian front-tracking for closed 2-D polygonal curves and 3-D triangulated surfaces. It builds on [FrontIntrinsicOps.jl] for geometry, normals, curvature, and DEC operators.\n\nThis documentation provides a quick overview, installation notes, usage examples, and focused pages on benchmarks, diagnostics, and remeshing.\n\nInstallation\nQuick start / Usage\nExamples\nAPI summary\nRunning tests\nPlotting and animations\nBenchmarks\nDiagnostics\nRedistribution & Remeshing\n\nFor more details, see the repository README and the inline docstrings in src/.","category":"section"}]
}
